rComments: Amazing professor, very easy to follow and extremely accessible for help outside of class. Would definitely take her class again.
good lecture slides, voice easy to follow
Assigns a Masive amounts of readings that are required for good test performance and overall understanding of whats going on in the class.
Prof Wong is very clear and draws on interesting examples to make her points. The lectures explain the material in a way that's easy to follow and understand.
Long Lectures! Moves way too fast. Forgets to take breaks. Discusses good interesting topics related to the study. Can be rude at times. Very to the point
Rude. Condescending. Not a bad instructor content wise.
Best political science prof I've ever had. Incredibly well organized, very clear, and well spoken. Overall great class.
The worst prof ever! Avoid at all costs. Rude. Makes no time for students. The worst instructions of all time.

I would highly recommend students to take the 412 seminar; itâ€™s a great way to interact on a more collegial basis, and a great way for the professor to develop a better understanding of your academic interests (read: letter of recommendations). The class is split with MA students, but as an undergrad I outscored most of them with a 4.0 overall.

Professor Wong is not a good professor. She is very moody. One day she is sweet, then the next day arrogant and rude. I think her idea of Statescraft was fun and interesting, which made the class interact in an exciting way. POL208 is a very interesting course in regards to material, but Professor Wong should not be teaching it.

Poorly written tests, useless and time-consuming assignment (a "fun" game that did not even function properly or teach us anything useful), condescending and late to office hours. Reads off slides. Would never take another class of hers again.

The worst instructor I've had at U of T. Cancelled class several times, had to bell curve a midterm 13% because it was written so poorly, condescending, discouraged students from attending office hours... avoid her classes.
Wong is a really nice person, but not a very good teacher. She does not explain expectations well, or provide any sort of helpful feedback. Does not make time for students.

Not a great course, no real instruction on assignments, poor feed back on papers, not worth the time. Although Wong is nice, she does not provide any real help to better understand what her expectations are.

Wong is one of those profs where you won't get an easy mark, but you'll come away from the course with a lot. If you put in the work, do the readings and show up and participate, she's a fair marker. If you do not do these things, do not expect a good mark. period.
Very clear lectures, but extremely difficult and unclear tests.

I had a great experience in Professor Wong's class. The seminar is well constructed, insofar as, students are allowed the freedom to engage and debate while Professor Wong directs and moderates.  She is by no means an easy Professor but if you read, attend, participate, and work hard, however, you will get the grade you deserve.
A great professor who knows a lot about human rights. The course is a bit demanding but if you put in the effort, you get the mark.
